<p>
  A transformer appears to be one of the simplest electrical devices — two coils of wire on a shared core — but it fails in at least five distinct ways, and each failure mode requires a different test to detect it. This guide covers every test from a basic multimeter winding resistance check to insulation resistance testing, polarity testing, and turns ratio measurement — the complete electrical commissioning and maintenance test sequence for transformers from small signal types up to large distribution units.
</p>

<h2 id="failure-modes">How Transformers Fail</h2>

<p>Understanding the failure modes shapes the test sequence. The five main failure mechanisms are:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Winding open circuit</strong>: A conductor break inside the winding — usually from a surge current or mechanical failure. The affected winding shows infinite resistance. Symptoms: no output voltage from the affected winding.</li>
  <li><strong>Winding short circuit (inter-turn fault)</strong>: Two adjacent turns of wire make contact, creating a shorted loop. This reduces the effective turns count, increases current, and causes localised overheating. Difficult to detect without an LCR meter or turns ratio tester.</li>
  <li><strong>Winding-to-core insulation breakdown</strong>: The insulation between the winding and the iron core fails — creating a ground fault. Detected by insulation resistance (megger) test.</li>
  <li><strong>Winding-to-winding insulation breakdown</strong>: Insulation between primary and secondary fails — creates a direct electrical path between them. Also detected by megger test. Particularly dangerous in isolating transformers where this destroys the safety isolation.</li>
  <li><strong>Core saturation / wrong turns ratio</strong>: Core damage, rewind errors, or connection errors cause abnormal turns ratio and may result in saturation under load. Detected by turns ratio test.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="winding-resistance">Test 1: DC Winding Resistance</h2>

<p>Winding resistance is the DC resistance of each winding's copper conductor. It is used to detect open circuits, poor connections, and inter-turn shorts (an inter-turn short reduces the effective length of the conductor and therefore reduces measured resistance).</p>

<p>Use a multimeter on the resistance range, or a dedicated low-resistance ohmmeter (micro-ohmmeter) for large transformers where winding resistance may be in the milliohm range.</p>

<ol>
  <li>Disconnect all external connections from the transformer.</li>
  <li>Measure the resistance between each pair of winding terminals. For a centre-tapped secondary, measure each half separately and the full winding.</li>
  <li>Compare readings between phases on three-phase transformers — they should be within ±2% of each other. Larger differences indicate a problem.</li>
  <li>Compare to the nameplate or design specification if available.</li>
</ol>

<Callout type="info" title="Large transformers have very low winding resistance">
  A 1000 kVA distribution transformer may have a primary winding resistance of 0.5 Ω and a secondary resistance of 3 mΩ. A standard multimeter cannot accurately measure milliohm values. Use a 4-wire (Kelvin) micro-ohmmeter for accurate results on large machines. The multimeter test is valid for small transformers (VA range) but not large ones.
</Callout>

