<h2 id="insulation-resistance">Test 2: Insulation Resistance (Megger Test)</h2>

<p>This test checks the insulation quality between windings and between each winding and the core/earth. Use a 500 V DC megger for transformers rated up to 1 kV; use 1000 V DC for HV transformers; use 2500 V DC or higher for power distribution transformers above 11 kV.</p>

<p>Perform three separate measurements:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Primary winding to earth</strong>: Connect megger Line terminal to the primary winding, Earth terminal to the core/tank. Short all primary terminals together and short all secondary terminals together and connect them to earth. Test for 1 minute.</li>
  <li><strong>Secondary winding to earth</strong>: Connect megger Line terminal to the secondary winding (all terminals shorted together), Earth terminal to core/tank. Primary terminals all shorted to earth. Test for 1 minute.</li>
  <li><strong>Primary to secondary</strong>: Connect megger Line terminal to primary (all shorted), Earth terminal to secondary (all shorted). Core/tank must be floating (disconnected from earth) for this test.</li>
</ol>

<p>Minimum acceptable insulation resistance values per IS 2026 (Power Transformers):</p>

<ul>
  <li>LV winding (up to 1.1 kV): minimum 200 MΩ (new), 100 MΩ (maintenance)</li>
  <li>HV windings: see manufacturer specification; typically ≥ 1000 MΩ for HV equipment in good condition</li>
  <li>Primary-to-secondary: must meet or exceed the lower of the two individual values</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="turns-ratio">Test 3: Turns Ratio Test</h2>

<p>The turns ratio test verifies that the voltage ratio between windings matches the nameplate specification and detects inter-turn short circuits that may not be visible in winding resistance measurements.</p>

<p><strong>Simple AC method</strong> (suitable for small transformers):</p>
<ol>
  <li>Apply a known, safe AC voltage to the primary (e.g., 230 V from the mains, or a lower voltage from a variac for safety).</li>
  <li>Measure the open-circuit secondary voltage with a multimeter in AC voltage mode.</li>
  <li>Calculate the ratio: Turns Ratio = V<sub>primary</sub> / V<sub>secondary</sub>. This should match the nameplate ratio within ±0.5% for a good transformer.</li>
</ol>

<Callout type="warning" title="Do not apply mains voltage to unknown or damaged HV transformers">
  For large or high-voltage transformers, use a dedicated transformer turns ratio (TTR) tester rather than applying mains voltage. A TTR tester applies a low AC voltage (typically 8 V AC) and measures the ratio with high precision. This is safe, accurate to ±0.1%, and can detect inter-turn shorts that change the ratio by small amounts invisible to a basic voltage measurement.
</Callout>

<h2 id="polarity">Test 4: Polarity Test</h2>

<p>Transformer polarity defines the phase relationship between primary and secondary voltages. Additive polarity means the voltages add when windings are connected in a specific way; subtractive polarity means they oppose. Polarity matters critically when:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Paralleling transformers (wrong polarity causes a short circuit)</li>
  <li>Connecting current transformers for metering and protection</li>
  <li>Building centre-tapped supplies (wrong polarity on one winding means half the output is wrong)</li>
</ul>

<p>Simple polarity test procedure:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Connect a short between one primary terminal (H1) and one secondary terminal (X1).</li>
  <li>Apply a known AC voltage to the primary (H1–H2).</li>
  <li>Measure the voltage between H2 and X2 (the remaining terminals).</li>
  <li>If the reading is V<sub>primary</sub> + V<sub>secondary</sub>: additive polarity. If V<sub>primary</sub> − V<sub>secondary</sub>: subtractive polarity.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="no-load-test">Test 5: No-Load (Open-Circuit) Test</h2>

<p>The no-load test measures the core losses (iron losses) and the magnetising current. It is performed by applying rated voltage at rated frequency to the primary with the secondary open-circuited:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Measure input power (using a wattmeter or power analyser) — this equals the core loss in watts</li>
  <li>Measure input current — this is the magnetising current, typically 0.5–3% of full-load current</li>
  <li>An abnormally high no-load current indicates core damage, incorrect core material, or core saturation</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="load-test">Test 6: Load Test (Short-Circuit Test)</h2>

<p>The short-circuit test determines winding impedance (copper losses) by applying a reduced voltage to the primary while the secondary is short-circuited through a current-limiting impedance. This test is typically done at a manufacturing facility with proper equipment, not in the field — it requires precise control to avoid dangerous currents. It determines:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Percentage impedance voltage (% Z) — important for fault current calculation</li>
  <li>Copper losses at full load</li>
  <li>Leakage inductance</li>
</ul>

<p>For field verification, compare the measured percentage impedance voltage to the nameplate value (typically 4–6% for distribution transformers). Values significantly outside specification indicate winding problems.</p>

<h2 id="transformer-oil">Oil-Filled Transformer Tests</h2>

<p>Large oil-filled power transformers require additional testing beyond the electrical tests above:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>BDV (Breakdown Voltage) test</strong>: Tests the dielectric strength of the transformer oil — the oil must withstand a high AC voltage across a standard gap before arcing. See our dedicated guide on the transformer oil BDV test.</li>
  <li><strong>Dissolved Gas Analysis (DGA)</strong>: Laboratory analysis of gases dissolved in the oil — specific gas signatures indicate specific fault types (overheating, arcing, partial discharge) before they become visible failures.</li>
  <li><strong>Moisture content</strong>: Water in transformer oil dramatically reduces its dielectric strength. Karl Fischer titration or capacitive moisture sensors measure oil water content in ppm.</li>
</ul>
